rs with publishers, critics, and members of the New York intelligentsia. Long unavailable in English, the journals have now been expertly retranslated by Ryan Bloom, with a new introduction by Alice Kaplan. Bloom’s translation captures the informal, sketch-like quality of Camus’s observations—by turns ironic, bitter, cutting, and melancholy—and the quick notes he must have taken after exhausting days of travel and lecturing. Bloom and Kaplan’s notes and annotations allow readers to walk beside the existentialist thinker as he experiences changes in his own life and the world around him, all in his inimitable style.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / General.2bisacsh1 aBloom, Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Alice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107973290 cprintz978022669495540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226750408423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226750408/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles